record_data.record_plain_text: 1. Availability. Seller will make wholesale electric energy, capacity, and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below. 2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all sales of energy, capacity, and ancillary services by Seller not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule of Seller. 3. Rates. All sales shall be made at the rates established between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 5. Compliance with Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller’s market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff. 6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market Based Rate Authority. Seller does not have any limitations on its market-based rate authority except as otherwise provided in this Tariff. The Commission granted Seller in RB Inyokern Solar WDAT 1203 LLC, Docket No. ER24-__-000 the following waivers and blanket authorization: (a) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission’s regulations requiring the filing of cost-of-service information, except for Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; (b) waiver of the requirements of Part 41 and Part 101, with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects; (c) waiver of Part 141 of the Commission’s regulations concerning accounting and reporting requirements, with the exception of 18 C.F.R. § 141.15; and (d) blanket approval as to Section 204 of the FPA and Part 34 of the Commission’s regulations for all future issuances of securities and debt and assumption of liabilities. 7. Ancillary Services. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (“PJM”) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (“CAISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (“SPP”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider’s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 8. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 1 Seller, as defined by 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a), in all regions. 9. Effective Date. This Tariff is effective on the date specified by the Commission. This Tariff shall continue in effect until terminated or changed in accordance with any applicable regulatory requirements.

WDAT 1203 and WDAT 1281 are collectively referred to herein as the "Project Companies" and individually as a "Project Company". The Project Companies, together with the Manager, are collectively referred to herein as the "Parties" and individually as a "Party". The terms "Project Company" and "Party" shall include the permitted successors and permitted assignees of such Person. Certain capitalized terms used in this Agreement are given defined meanings in Appendix A attached hereto. RECITALS A. WDAT 1203 has entered into that Ground Lease with Dimension RE LLC, dated September 18, 2023 (the "1203 Lease Agreement"), which is evidenced by that certain Memorandum of Lease, recorded on September 25, 2023, in the Official Records of Kern County, California, as Instrument No. 223116064, as well as that Construction, Interconnection, Transmission and Access Easement Agreement with Dimension RE LLC (the "1203 Easement"), dated September 18, 2023, for certain land located in Kern County, California, recorded on September 25, 2023, in the Official Records of Kern County, California, as Instrument No. 223116063. WDAT 1203 owns, is constructing, and will operate the approximately 20 MW(AC) photovoltaic solar project more specifically described in Exhibit A. The land subject to the 1203 Lease Agreement is described in Exhibit A-1 to this Agreement (the "1203 Property"). The land subject to the 1203 Easement is described in Exhibit A-2 to this Agreement (the "1203 Easement Area") B. WDAT 1281 has entered into that Ground Lease with Dimension RE LLC, dated September 18, 2023 (the "1281 Lease Agreement"), which is evidenced by that certain Memorandum of Lease, recorded on September 28, 2023, in the Official Records of Kern County, California, as Instrument No. 223117562, as well as that Construction, Transmission, Interconnection, and Access Easement Agreement with Dimension RE LLC (the "1281 Easement") dated September 18, 2023, for certain land located in Kern County, California, recorded on September 25, 2023 in the Official Records of Kern County, California as Instrument No. 223115828. WDAT 1281 owns, is constructing, and will operate the approximately 12 MW (AC) photovoltaic solar project more specifically described in Exhibit B. The land subject to the 1281 Lease Agreement is described in Exhibit B-1 to this Agreement (the "1281 Property"). The land subject to the 1281 Easement is described in Exhibit B-2 to this Agreement (the "1281 Easement Area"). C. The 1203 Easement and the 1281 Easement shall be referred to collectively as the "Easements." The 1203 Easement Area and the 1281 Easement Area shall be collectively referred to as the "Easement Area." 1 D. The Parties desire to share such facilities described in Exhibit D in accordance with the terms of this Agreement. E. WDAT 1203 entered into a Generator Interconnection Agreement, effective April 14, 2017, a Service Agreement for Wholesale Distribution Service, effective April 14, 2017, between Southern California Edison Company and R L Capital, Inc., as amended by that First Amendment effective as of October 1, 2019, both of which were assigned to WDAT 1203 pursuant to that Assignment and Assumption Agreement between R L Capital, Inc. and WDAT 1203 dated March 29, 2022, and as further amended by that Second Amendment to the Generator Interconnection Agreement between WDAT 1203 and Southern California Edison Company, dated November 15, 2022 (as assigned and amended, the "WDAT 1203 Interconnection Agreement"). F. G. The Project Companies wish to share the use and cost of certain electrical transmission, communications and other structures and facilities and associated real property rights (including, without limitation, certain surface waivers, rights of way, and easements), and to engage Manager to construct, operate, maintain, repair and manage the foregoing, all in accordance with and subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. H. The Project Companies also wish to provide for the appointment of a Manager for provision of certain services with respect to the Shared Facilities and the obligations under the Interconnection Agreements, at such time and on the terms and conditions contained herein. NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged by the Parties, the Parties agree as follows: ARTICLE 1 DEFINITIONS AND INTERPRETATIONS 1.1 Definitions. As used in this Agreement, including the Recitals to this Agreement, and except as required by grammatical usage and apart from proper nouns, each capitalized term has the meaning given to it in this Agreement and in the Schedule of Definitions attached as Appendix A. 1.2 Interpretation. In this Agreement, unless a clear, contrary intention appears: 2 (a) the singular includes the plural and vice versa; (b) reference to any Person includes such Person's successors and assigns but, in the case of a Project Company, only if such assigns are permitted by this Agreement, and reference to a Person in a particular capacity excludes such Person in any other capacity; (c) reference to any gender ncludes each other gender; (d) reference to any agreement (including this Agreement), document or instrument means such agreement, document or instrument as amended or modified and in effect from time to time in accordance with the terms thereof and, if applicable, the terms of this Agreement; (e) reference to any applicable law means such law as amended, modified, codified, or reenacted, in whole or in part, and in effect from time to time, including, if applicable, rules and regulations promulgated thereunder; reference to any Section means such Section of this Agreement, and references in any Section or definition to any clause means such clause of such Section or definition; (g) "hereunder," "hereof," "hereto" and words of similar import shall be deemed references to this Agreement as a whole and not to any particular Section or other provision of this Agreement; (h) "including" means including without limiting the generality of any description such term; and (i) relative to the determination of any period of time, "from" means "from and including", "to" means "to but excluding" and "through" means "through and including". ARTICLE 2 EASEMENT AREA 2.1 Declaration of Intention. The Project Companies hereby declare that their relationship in and to the Shared Facilities is and will be that of tenants in common, and that each Project Company will have an undivided interest in the Shared Facilities on and subject to the terms, conditions, limitations and requirements set forth in this Agreement and the Bill of Sale. The arrangements and ownership structure contemplated by this Agreement are not being made with the intention or expectation of producing revenue or making or sharing in any profits from the ownership or operation of the Shared Facilities, but are instead intended as a form of legal ownership whereby the Project Companies can accomplish their respective objectives of independently owning and operating their respective undivided interests in, and sharing the use of, the Shared Facilities in connection with their respective Projects and businesses and to 3 enable the Project Companies to perform and discharge certain of their obligations under the Interconnection Agreements and their respective Power Purchase Agreements. 2.2 Easement Area. (a) Pursuant to the Easements, each of the Project Companies has rights and interests in the Easement Area and agrees that such interests (the "Easement Property Rights") may be used to the extent necessary to allow for the development, design, construction, operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities. Each Project Company agrees to perform all of its respective obligations under the Easements, to maintain the Easements in full force and effect and to promptly and completely cure any defaults or events of default thereunder for which it is responsible. (b) Each Project Company hereby consents to the use of the Easement Property Rights by the other Project Company and Manager pursuant to this Agreement, including without limitation, where such Easement Property Rights affect, or otherwise touch and concern, other real property interests or estates held by such Project Company so long as such use is consistent with the requirements of this Agreement and the rights of the Parties hereunder. 2.3 Interests in Shared Facilities. (a) On fifteen (15) days' prior written notice, pursuant to the Bill of Sale, the form of which is attached as Exhibit I, WDAT 1203 will convey to WDAT 1281, as tenants in common, an undivided ownership interest in and to any and all of the Shared Facilities. Each of the Project Companies shall own, hold, and utilize its undivided interest in the Shared Facilities in accordance with the terms of this Agreement. ( ) As a result of the transfer and conveyance in the Bill of Sale, the applicable Proportionate Share of each Project Company in the Shared Facilities shall be as set forth on Exhibit E. 2.4 Access to the Easement Area and Shared Facilities. (a) By Project Companies. Subject to the conditions and additional rights described below, each Project Company and any Secured Party of such Project Company upon the occurrence of an Event of Default (under and as defined in the applicable agreement with the Secured Party) shall have access to and to enter onto the Easement Area and the Shared Facilities to the extent reasonably necessary for (i) inspection of such Easement Area and the Shared Facilities located thereon, without unduly interfering with the normal operations of the other Project Company or the Manager and otherwise subject to the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement, (ii) construction or operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities in the event the Manager fails to do so, in accordance with the terms hereof, or (iii) for ingress and egress to and from, and for maintenance or repair of, the Shared Facilities in the event of an Emergency and the failure or unavailability of the Manager or its representatives to 4 respond timely to such Emergency. Except in the event of an Emergency, the accessing Project Company shall give the other Project Company and the Manager at least forty-eight (48) hours prior notice of its intent to enter upon the Easement Area (said notice may be by telephone, e-mail, or any other recognized electronic means in addition to any other methods of notice authorized herein). In the event of an Emergency, prior notice is not required, but the Project Company shall give notice of entry onto the Easement Area as soon as reasonably practicable thereafter. Any Project Company entering on the Easement Area or accessing the Shared Facilities shall follow all written safety and security procedures adopted by the Project Companies and/or the Manager with respect to the Easement Area and/or the Shared Facilities. (b) By Manager. The Manager shall have access to the Easement Area and Shared Facilities at any time for purposes of complying with its obligations set forth in this Agreement, including (i) inspection of such Easement Area and the Shared Facilities located thereon, without unduly interfering with the normal operations of the Project Companies and otherwise subject to the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement, (ii) construction or operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities in accordance with the terms hereof, or (iii) for ingress and egress to and from, and for maintenance or repair of, the Shared Facilities. The Manager shall follow all written safety and security procedures adopted by the Project Companies with respect to the Easement Area. (c) By Secured Parries. A Secured Party of a Project Company, upon the occurrence of an Event of Default (under and as defined in the applicable agreement with the Secured Party), shall have the right to enter onto the Easement Area related to such Project Company's project for the purposes described in Section 2.4(a)(i) and, in connection with or following the exercise of remedies by the Secured Party under its Security Documents, for the other purposes described in Section 2.4(a), in each case upon five (5) Business Days' advance written notice of its entry delivered to the Manager and the other Project Company; provided that such right of entry shall be limited to normal business hours except in the case of an Emergency. Any Secured Party so entering on the Easement Area or accessing the Shared Facilities shall (i) follow all written safety and security procedures and other site regulations of the Project Companies and/or the Manager with respect to the Easement Area and/or the Shared Facilities, and (ii) not unduly interfere with the normal operations of the Project Companies and the Manager thereon. 2.5 No Interference. Each Project Company's use of the Easement Area and the Shared Facilities shall not interfere with the use and enjoyment by any other Project Company of its respective rights in such Easement Area or Shared Facilities, subject to all the terms and provisions of this Agreement. Each Project Company shall cooperate in good faith to accommodate each other Project Company's use of the Easement Area and the Shared Facilities for the benefit of such other Project Company's Project. Subject to the first sentence of this Section 2.5 the use of the Easement Area and the Shared Facilities by the Project Companies pursuant to and in accordance with the terms of this Agreement will not, separately or in the aggregate, be deemed to constitute an overburdening of the Easement Area or the Shared Facilities or any portion of either of them. 5 2.6 Construction of Shared Facilities. (a) Construction of Shared Facilities. WDAT 1203 shall procure, install and construct the Shared Facilities on behalf of the Project Companies pursuant to the EPC Contract and shall, immediately upon receipt of title to the Shared Facilities under the EPC Contract, assign and convey to WDAT 1281 title as a tenant in common to the Shared Facilities pursuant to the Bill of Sale in proportion to its Proportionate Share. WDAT 1203 shall diligently commence and complete construction of the Shared Facilities in accordance with the EPC Contract. (b) Payment of Shared Facilities Construction Costs. WDAT 1203 shall be responsible for all costs incurred for design, installation and construction of the Shared Facilities. 2.7 Additional Premises Rights or Facilities. (a) Approval of Additional Premises Rights or Facilities. To the extent that any additional premises or rights in premises (other than the Easement Property Rights existing as of the Agreement Date) that relate to the Shared Facilities or operation thereof (the "Additional Premises Rights") or any additional facilities, improvements, modifications, or upgrades of facilities that relate to the Shared Facilities or operation thereof ("Additional Facilities") (i) are required in order to construct, use, operate, maintain or repair the Shared Facilities, (ii) are required by any Project Company for the construction, use, operation, maintenance or repair of its Project, or (iii) are needed or would materially benefit, in the reasonable belief of the Manager, the interconnection or operation of the Projects collectively, a Project Company or the Manager, as applicable, may give written notice to the other Parties of such requirement, with a reasonable explanation why such Additional Premises Rights and/or Additional Facilities are needed and demonstrating that such Additional Premises Rights and/or Additional Facilities will not, taken as a whole, have an adverse effect on the Shared Facilities or any Project. (1) Each Project Company shall, within thirty (30) days after receiving such notice, notify the Manager and the other Project Companies in writing of its election to participate or not to participate in such Additional Premises Rights and/or Additional Facilities, as applicable. Failure to notify the other Project Company of its election to participate shall be deemed an election not to participate. (2) If acquisition of the Additional Premises Rights and/or Additional Facilities is approved by all of the Project Companies, they shall be acquired in the name of the Project Companies as tenants in common in proportion to their respective Proportionate Shares and shall become Easement Property Rights and/or Shared Facilities, as applicable, hereunder. 6 (3) Following acquisition of any Additional Premises Rights and/or Additional Facilities, the Parties will amend the exhibits hereto as necessary to reflect such new Easement Property Rights and/or Shared Facilities. (b) Disapproved Additional Premises Rights or Additional Facilities. If any proposed Additional Premises Rights or Additional Facilities are not approved pursuant to the provisions of Section 2.7(a) above, but the requirements of Section 2.7(c) below are satisfied and any additional facilities, improvements, modifications or upgrades are constructed and installed in accordance with Governmental Requirements and Good Utility Practice, then nothing herein shall prevent a Project Company from acquiring such property rights ("Disapproved Premises Rights") or installing such additional facilities, improvements, modifications or upgrades ("Disapproved Additional Facilities") in its own name. Any such Disapproved Premises Rights and Disapproved Facilities shall not be deemed Easement Property Rights or Shared Facilities hereunder. (c) Requirements of All Additional Premises Rights and Additional Facilities. No Additional Premises Rights (including any Disapproved Additional Premises Rights) shall be acquired by any Project Company, and no Additional Facilities (including any Disapproved Additional Facilities) may be acquired, constructed or installed by any Project Company if such acquisition, construction or installation could reasonably be expected to (i) result in an Emergency, (ii) violate the terms of this Agreement, any other Easement Property Right, any Interconnection Agreements, any Power Purchase Agreement, any tax equity agreement or any Security Documents, or (iii) have any more than an insignificant adverse effect on the operation, performance, reliability or maintenance costs of any Project (except as may be agreed by the Party owning such Project), or the operation, performance, reliability or Operation and Maintenance Costs of the Shared Facilities; provided, however, that if requested by the Project Company proposing to acquire, construct or install the Additional Premises Rights or the Additional Facilities, a Project Company will use commercially reasonable efforts to obtain any necessary consents under the tax equity documents or Security Documents, as applicable, related to its Project to allow the acquisition, construction and/or installation of such Additional Premises Rights or Additional Facilities. 2.8 Covenants Running with the Land. The covenants of the Project Companies made in this Agreement shall be deemed to be covenants running with and binding upon the land pursuant to applicable law for the duration of the term of this Agreement and shall bind and benefit all current and future owners of the lands bound and benefited by this Agreement, including the Easement Area, Easement Property Rights, the Additional Premises Rights and the Property. 2.9 Liens. No Party shall, directly or indirectly, create, incur or permit to exist any lien on the Easement Area, the Easement Property Rights or the Shared Facilities, either as a whole or in a Party's undivided interest therein, except for (a) liens for financing purposes as provided in Section 8.3 and (b) Permitted Liens. If any lien not permitted under the previous sentence attaches to any of the Easement Area, the Easement Property Rights or the Shared Facilities, or if a Party receives notice of any such lien, the Party whose actual or alleged act or omission resulted in such lien shall cause such lien to be released and removed of record within fifteen 7 (15) days of such attachment or notice. Failure of a Party to remove such lien as required under this Section 2.9 shall entitle each other Party to cause such lien to be removed and the costs thereof shall be promptly reimbursed by the Party responsible hereunder for removal of such lien, plus expenses and interest at the Default Interest Rate. Notwithstanding the forgoing, nothing herein shall require a Project Company to remove a lien that relates to its separate property interest in property that is also located on or within the Easement Area other than an Easement Property Right hereunder, if such lien relates to such Project Company's rights in and to that portion of the Easement Area by virtue of a separate lease, easement or license agreement and that is not a Easement Property Right hereunder. 2.10 Payment and Reimbursement. Manager may, from time to time, submit to each Project Company: (i) a statement of Shared O M Expenses for such Project Company's Proportionate Share, if any, incurred by such Project Company during the period to which such statement applies; and (ii) an invoice for payment of such Project Company's Proportionate Share of approved Additional Facilities construction costs and Shared O M Expenses. Each such invoice shall be payable by the invoiced Project Company within fifteen (15) days after receipt of an invoice, with backup documentation, from the Manager setting forth the amount that is due. If a Project Company disputes the invoiced amount, it shall nonetheless pay the disputed amount, and shall refer the issue for resolution in accordance with the provisions of Article 13. Any disputed amount that is finally determined by dispute resolution pursuant to Article 13 or by mutual agreement to have been improperly invoiced shall be promptly refunded to the Project Company. All sums not paid when due shall thereafter bear interest at the Default Interest Rate. Each Project Company shall have the right to audit, and receive supporting documentation for, any expenses or other amounts required to be paid by such Project Company hereunder. ARTICLE 3 ALLOCATION AND PAYMENT OF O M EXPENSES 3.1 Expenses of Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities and Easement Area. The operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities and Easement Area shall be performed in accordance with the requirements set forth in Article 5 below. The expenses of such operation and maintenance shall be allocated among the Project Companies and paid as provided in this Article 3. (a) Shared O M Expenses. Each Project Company shall be responsible for and shall pay its Proportionate Share of the expenses and liabilities relating to operation and maintenance, including all allocable payments under the O M Agreement, all FERC compliance costs, costs of labor and materials and accounting, general and administrative costs, and the Manager Fee (collectively, "Shared O M Expenses"). Where possible, Shared O M Expenses shall be allocated to the Project for which such Shared O M Expenses were incurred. If it is not reasonably possible to allocate such Shared O M Expenses, they shall be allocated to both Project Companies in accordance with their Proportionate Shares. 8 (b) Step-In Rights; Indemnity. If any Project Company fails to pay its share of O M Expenses as and when due, including any amounts that may be due to the Manager hereunder, then, upon at least five (5) days' written notice to the defaulting Project Company, the other Project Company may, but shall not be obligated to, advance any amounts which such defaulting Project Company failed to pay, and such defaulting Project Company shall promptly reimburse the other Project Company upon demand for all such amounts advanced on behalf of the defaulting Project Company, together with interest thereon from the date advanced to the date repaid at the Default Interest Rate. 3.2 Annual Statements; Payment Adjustments. In addition to the reports under Section 5.7, within thirty (30) days after the end of each calendar year, the Manager shall provide the Project Companies an annual statement of all actual Shared O M Expenses during the previous calendar year, all payments made by each Project Company on account of Shared O M Expenses, and a reconciliation of the amounts paid by each such Project Company against such Project Company's Proportionate Share of the actual Shared O M Expenses during such calendar year. If any Project Company's share of such Shared O M Expenses exceeds the amounts paid by such Project Company, such Project Company shall pay the amount of such difference to the Manager as part of the next monthly invoice. If any Project Company's share of such Shared O M Expenses is less than the amounts paid by such Project Company, the Manager shall credit the amount of such overpayment by such Project Company against future invoiced amounts from the Manager until such credit is exhausted. 3.3 Property Taxes and Assessments. The Manager shall allocate all property taxes on the attributable Easement Property Rights and Shared Facilities to the Project Companies in proportion to their respective Proportionate Shares. Each Project Company shall have the right, in its sole discretion, to contest by legal proceedings (which may be brought in the name of such Project Company) the validity or the amount of any assessments or taxes attributable to the Easement Property Rights or Shared Facilities for which the Parties are responsible hereunder. Each Project Company shall in all respects cooperate with the other Project Company in any such contest. Such costs shall be deemed a Shared O M Expense and shall be reimbursable by the Project Companies regardless of whether included in the Approved Shared Facilities Budget. 3.4 Costs of Repair Work. The Manager shall charge the costs of Repairs of Shared Facilities, and for other work or services provided by the Manager, including costs paid to third parties, at the actual cost to the Manager therefor. 3.5 Shared Facilities O M Budget. (a) No later than sixty (60) days prior to the beginning of each calendar year during the term hereof, the Manager shall prepare and submit to the Parties a proposed budget for operation and maintenance of the Easement Area and Shared Facilities for the following calendar year (each, a "Shared Facilities O M Budget") which budget shall include the estimated cost of all anticipated Shared O M Expenses during the following year; provided that, such Shared Facilities O M Budget shall not include the cost of construction of the Shared Facilities or any Additional Facilities, which costs shall be 9 governed by the applicable provisions of Article 2. The Shared Facilities O M Budget shall set forth the respective amounts allocated to the Project Companies in accordance with Exhibit E hereto. When approved pursuant to subparagraph (b) below, the Shared Facilities O M Budget shall be the "Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget" for such year. (b) The Shared Facilities O M Budget shall be subject to the approval of all of the Project Companies (such approval not to be unreasonably withheld); provided, however, that the portion of the Shared Facilities O M Budget reflecting the cost and expenses to be paid pursuant to the O M Agreement and any other third party operations and maintenance agreement entered into by Manager consistently with this Agreement are deemed approved Shared O M Expenses hereunder. The Project Companies shall give their approval or disapproval of the Shared Facilities O M Budget no later than thirty (30) days after receipt thereof from the Manager; provided that, pending approval, Manager may operate and maintain the Shared Facilities based on the Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget for the previous calendar year, as adjusted by the Inflation Adjustment Factor; provided that any single extraordinary expense in excess of ten percent (10%) of the last Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget shall not be incurred without the prior approval of all of the Project Companies. (c) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, the Manager shall be permitted to, in its reasonable discretion, incur, or cause the incurrence, on behalf of the Project Companies, costs and expenses for the operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities in a given year in an amount not to exceed ten percent (10%) in excess of the Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget and any expenses needed to ensure safe operation of the Shared Facilities and return the Shared Facilities from any outage, and such excess expenses shall be deemed approved Shared O M Expenses hereunder. 3.6 Other Expenses Caused By Parties. Notwithstanding the provisions of this Agreement, any costs, claims, loss or other liability to third parties arising from the actions or inactions of a Party in violation or breach of the covenants herein or the provisions of any Easement Property Right, the Interconnection Agreements, or the Power Purchase Agreements shall be the responsibility of such Party to the extent not covered by the policies of insurance required under Article 7 below, provided that such Party shall pay all deductibles due under such policies with respect thereto. 3.7 Rights of Other Party for Non-Payment. If a Party (a "Non-Paying Party") fails to timely make any required payment of amounts due under Article 2 or this Article 3, one or more of the other Parties may make such payment on behalf of such Non-Paying Party and the amount so paid shall be immediately due and payable from the Non-Paying Party to such other Party or Parties, together with interest at the Default Interest Rate from the date paid until repaid to such other Party or Parties. 10 ARTICLE 4 OTHER RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS OF THE PARTIES 4.1 Maximum Capacity of Projects. The Maximum Capacity means, with respect to the each Project, the maximum net generation capacity of such Project, each as set forth in Exhibit F which Maximum Capacity may be changed only in accordance with this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreements, provided that the combined Maximum Capacity of the Projects shall not exceed the maximum net generation capacity of the Projects at the Point of Interconnection, as identified and described the Interconnection Agreements. Each Project Company shall be authorized to construct its Project with a nameplate capacity of up to, but not in excess of, the Maximum Capacity for such Project as set forth on Exhibit F (at any time, the "Permitted Capacity"). 4.2 Manager Access to Projects.. The Project Companies hereby grant Manager all access rights that it needs to perform its obligations hereunder. 4.3 Maintenance and Repair of Projects. Without limiting each Project Company's obligations under the Interconnection Agreements, each Project Company shall, at its sole cost and expense, maintain in good working order and repair at all times each part of its Project which connects with or may affect the Shared Facilities or the Easement Area. 4.4 Termination or Modification of Any Easement Property Right. No Project Company shall terminate any Easement Property Rights nor permit any Easement Property Rights to expire prior to the expiration of this Agreement without the prior written consent of all of the other Project Company. Further, no Project Company shall (i) subject to the following subsection (ii), modify or amend any of the Easement Property Rights in any way without the prior written consent of the other Project Company, or (ii) modify or amend any of the Easement Property Rights in a manner that materially, adversely affects a Project Company without the prior written consent of that Project Company; provided, however, that if a Project Company intends to abandon or cease operation of its Project, it may do so only in accordance with Article 9 below. 4.5 Standard of Performance. Each Party shall perform its obligations under this Agreement (i) in accordance with all requirements of this Agreement, all Governmental Requirements, Good Utility Practice, the Easement Property Rights, and the Interconnection Agreements and any applicable requirements of FERC, NERC or the CAISO, and (ii) in a manner that is (A) non-discriminatory, and (B) attempts to maximize the delivery of energy and energy-related products from the Projects to the Point of Interconnection at a reasonable cost. 4.6 Party Representatives. On or promptly after the Agreement Date, each Party shall by written notice to the other Parties designate an individual representative of such Party and an alternate (the "Party Representative") whose instructions, requests, and decisions will be binding upon such Party in all matters concerning this Agreement, except that the Party's Representative shall not have the authority to amend this Agreement. Each Party shall have the right to change such Party's Representative at any time and from time to time by written notice to the other Parties. 11 4.7 No Warranties. No Party makes any warranty, express or implied with respect to the Shared Facilities, the Easement Area, the Additional Facilities, or Qualified Replacement Components. THE FOREGOING EXCLUSION OF ALL WARRANTIES BY EACH PARTY INCLUDES IMPLIED WARRANTIES OF SUITABILITY AND FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE. 4.8 Withdrawal of Party. Subject to the provisions of this Section 4.8, if a Project Company determines that it will cease operation of or otherwise abandon its Project or not require any Easement Property Rights or Shared Facilities hereunder, such Project Company shall have the right to withdraw from this Agreement, subject to the requirements of Article 9 provided written notice thereof is given to the other Parties. Following such permitted withdrawal, the withdrawing Project Company shall have no further right of access to or use of the Shared Facilities and shall execute such documents as necessary to transfer its ownership interest in the Shared Facilities to the other Project Company. No such withdrawal shall release the withdrawing Project Company from any indemnification or reimbursement obligations that arise prior to the effective date of its withdrawal, including its obligation to pay its Proportionate Share of Shared O M Expenses and all applicable costs described in Sections 9.2, 9.3 and 9.4. 4.9 No Waste or Nuisance. To the extent that a Party has the authority under this Agreement (or any applicable third party agreement) to prevent such actions or inactions, no Party will use or permit the use of the Shared Facilities, any Easement Property Rights or Shared Facilities Services in any manner that would create waste or nuisance, or that would increase the rate, or jeopardize the issuance or maintenance, of any insurance policy relating to the Shared Facilities, any Easement Property Rights or any Project, nor otherwise conduct or cause to be conducted operations on its Properties which would have similar effects on, or otherwise damage or interfere with, the Shared Facilities, any Easement Property Rights or any other Project. The Parties will at all times while conducting their respective operations make commercially reasonable efforts to minimize the impact of such operations and activities upon the other Parties. 4.10 No Public Access. The Parties agree that, except as required to comply with the terms of a Easement Property Right or unless so ordered by a Governmental Authority, there will be no general public access to the Easement Area or the Shared Facilities. The Parties shall undertake to cooperate in enforcing such requirement for limiting access to the Easement Area and the Shared Facilities, including establishing and enforcing procedures for safety and security. 4.11 Competing Ventures. Any Party may engage in or possess an interest in other business ventures of any nature and description, independently or with others, including but not limited to the ownership, financing, leasing, management, syndication, investment, brokerage and development of real property (including real property of the same type and nature as the Projects), and no Party shall have any right by virtue of this Agreement in and to such independent ventures or to the income or profits derived therefrom. 12 4.12 FERC Filings. This Agreement will be filed for acceptance with FERC as a rate filing under section 205 of the FPA. Promptly after the Agreement Date and after any amendment to the Agreement that is required to be filed at FERC, the Parties will cooperate in the preparation of a filing by the Manager, on behalf of the Project Companies, acceptable to all Parties to seek acceptance by FERC of the Agreement or such amendment and the Manager, on behalf of the Project Companies, will file the Agreement or such amendment for acceptance by FERC. WDAT 1281 will file a certificate of concurrence to the Manager's rate filing with FERC at the time the Manager's rate filing is made. Each of the Parties agrees that it will cooperate in the preparation of such filings and as necessary to address any issues raised by FERC in connection with the filing for acceptance of the Agreement or such amendment. Subject to the terms and conditions set forth herein, the Parties agree to execute and deliver all documents reasonably necessary for this Agreement to comply with FERC requirements. The cost of all required filings at FERC shall be included in Shared O M Expenses. 4.13 Conflict Among Agreements. In the event of any conflict between the Manager's obligations under this Agreement or Interconnection Agreements, the terms of the Interconnection Agreements shall prevail. The Manager shall notify the Project Companies in writing if it becomes aware of any such conflict and the Parties shall discuss whether amendments to this Agreement are necessary to address such matters. 4.14 Co-Tenancy and Interconnection Agreements. (a) As soon as practicable, but no less than forty-five (45) days prior to the expected interconnection date for the WDAT 1281 Project, WDAT 1281 shall provide the Manager and the other Project Company with the proposed schedule, plans and requirements with respect to the interconnection of the WDAT 1281 Project to the Shared Facilities, together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, including dates and times of such construction and curtailment or disconnection, if any. WDAT 1281 shall keep the Manager reasonably informed regarding the anticipated interconnection date. WDAT 1281 and the Manager shall cooperate and coordinate plans to assemble, construct and install any applicable interconnection facilities and to install meters, bus interfaces and other interconnection equipment in and with the Shared Facilities; provided, however, that no such cooperation or coordination will unreasonably delay the interconnection of the WDAT 1281 to the Shared Facilities; and provided, further, that any disputes relating to such schedule, plans or requirements will be submitted for resolution in accordance with the Technical Dispute resolution procedures set forth in Article 13. Each Project Company will have sole responsibility for the costs of interconnection of its Project with the Shared Facilities. (b) The Parties acknowledge that all or some of the WDAT 1203 Project may be required to be taken off-line or reduce production during the installation of the WDAT 1281 Project (any such period being the "1281 Caused Downtime"). WDAT 1281 shall compensate WDAT 1203 for any revenue losses incurred by the WDAT 1203 under the applicable PPA as a result of 1281 Caused Downtime; provided that, WDAT 1203 shall provide the requisite documentation to demonstrate that such revenue losses resulted solely from the 1281Caused Downtime and shall notify WDAT 1281 within ten (10) 13 Business Days of WDAT 1203 having procured or obtained the information related to such accrual of lost revenue. The reimbursement of revenue losses is WDAT 1281 exclusive obligation and WDAT 1203's exclusive remedy with respect to 1281 Caused Downtime. For clarity, if the installation, commissioning, or any other work on the WDAT 1281 Project is performed during non-insolation hours or during any period in which the WDAT 1203 would already have been off-line for any reason, then such period shall not apply in the determination of 1281 Caused Downtime. (c) Meters. Each Project Company will install and maintain revenue meters for its own Project, which meters will be installed between the respective Projects and the point of interconnection to the Shared Facilities. ARTICLE 5 OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF THE EASEMENT AREA AND THE SHARED FACILITIES 5.1 In General. The Manager shall perform the Operations and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities in accordance with this Agreement and applicable law. Maintenance of the Shared Facilities shall include the responsibilities listed in Exhibit G. The costs and expenses incurred to maintain the Shared Facilities shall be incurred and shared in accordance with Article 3. The Manager shall have the right to enter into an operations and maintenance agreement ("O M Agreement") with a third party operation and maintenance provider to perform some or all of such services, and payments by the Manager under the O M Agreement will be Shared O M Expenses as provided in Section 3.1(a). As long as each of the Manager and each Project Company are Affiliates of each other and with Dimension RE LLC, the O M responsibilities hereunder may be included in an Operations and Maintenance Agreement between the Project Companies and Dimension RE LLC. Each Project Company shall cooperate with the Manager in the performance of the Operations and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities. 5.2 Specific Authority. Without limiting the authority of the Manager pursuant to Section 5.1 but subject to the limitations of authority of the Manager in Section 5.3 below, the Manager shall have the power, without further consent or approval of the Parties: (a) To perform operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities, including without limitation the responsibilities listed in Exhibit G and any Repairs subject to the requirements of Section 5.4 below. (b) Subject to Section 5.4 to negotiate, enter into, execute, acknowledge or amend agreements relating to the operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities, provided that (i) no such actions would reasonably be expected to adversely affect the rights or privileges of the Parties except with respect to incurring additional expenses for the accounts of the Parties that are within the Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget (and any amounts in excess thereof permitted under this Agreement) and (ii) the Manager shall provide each Party with copies of any such agreement promptly upon execution thereof; 14 (c) To (i) exercise all of the Project Companies' rights under the warranties with respect to the Shared Facilities, Additional Facilities or Repairs, as applicable; (ii) monitor and report to the Project Companies concerning the remaining terms of any such warranties; (iii) perform such inspections as are reasonable to ensure that any final warranty work is not required prior to the expiration of any such warranty, and (iv) prepare and prosecute warranty claims, if reasonably necessary to enforce any such warranties; (d) To employ from time to time, at the expense of the Project Companies but subject to the Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget, persons, firms or corporations to perform Operations and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities, including entering into an O M Agreement; (e) To pay and collect amounts due in connection with the Easement Property Rights and Shared Facilities, and to maintain one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Manager in connection with its duties hereunder shall be maintained; To expend monies necessary for operation and maintenance in accordance with the Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget (including any amounts in excess thereof permitted under this Agreement); (g) To commit to the expenditure of or spend such amounts for and on behalf of the Project Companies as are reasonably necessary to expedite Repairs to the Shared Facilities due to an Emergency, provided that the Manager gives concurrent notice by facsimile or electronic mail to such Project Companies regarding the nature and amount of the expenditure as soon as reasonably practicable after the estimated amount of the expenditure is known by the Manager, but in any event no later than the time the Manager commits to the expenditure; and (h) To negotiate with, and represent the Parties' interests before, any Governmental Authority regarding property valuation and real property taxes (if any) related to the Easement Property Rights and Shared Facilities. 5.3 Limitation on Authority. (a) The Manager shall not, without the approval of both of the Project Companies: (1) Amend, modify or waive the terms of this Agreement or the Interconnection Agreements (to the extent an amendment of a Project Company's Interconnection Agreement could impact the other Project Company or the Parties' use of the Shared Facilities); (2) Create or cause to be created any lien or encumbrance on the Easement Property Rights or the Shared Facilities, other than a Permitted Encumbrance; 15 (3) Perform or omit to perform any act which would cause any person reasonably to believe that the Manager is authorized to bind the Project Companies, except as expressly permitted under this Agreement; (4) Sell, assign, mortgage, encumber, convey or otherwise transfer all or any portion of (i) the Easement Property Rights or Easement Area, or any interest or estate therein, or (ii) any Shared Facilities or any of the components thereof, other than the trade-in, sale or transfer of assets related thereto that are worn out, obsolete or no longer necessary or useful for the operation thereof; (5) Borrow funds on behalf of the Project Companies; or (6) Agree to any restrictions or limitations on the Easement Area, the Easement Property Rights or the Shared Facilities that do not exist as of the Agreement Date; (7) Take any action to voluntarily and permanently remove any Shared Facilities from service, except to the extent they are being replaced with new or repaired facilities; or (8) Take any action which could reasonably be expected to have a material adverse effect on the ability of any Project Company to use the Shared Facilities or the Easement Property Rights; except as required or permitted under this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreements or any Power Purchase Agreement. (b) The Manager shall not, without the unanimous approval of the Project Companies: (1) Incur expenses except in accordance with this Agreement and/or the Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget in any calendar year except as provided in this Agreement; (2) Except as provided in the Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget, enter into any commitments, contracts or other agreements requiring expenditures in excess of One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00) or with a duration of more than one (1) year except for (i) permitted expenditures in the case of an Emergency or as contemplated by the Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget, or (ii) expenditures under the EPC Contract, the O M Agreement or approved amendment thereto; (c) Except as permitted under Sections 7.9 and 7.10 procure insurance coverage that is less than the coverage required under Article 7. or (d) Enter into or materially modify any agreement with any Affiliate of the Manager except on terms and conditions, including price, that are at least as favorable to the Project Companies as would be obtained from an unaffiliated third party. 16 5.4 Repairs. (a) The Manager shall have the right to replace or repair, or to cause to be replaced or repaired, any component or group of components of the Shared Facilities (i) with an aggregate cost of One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00) or less, or (ii) that must be repaired to ensure the continued safe operation of the Shared Facilities or to return the Shared Facilities to service, with a Qualified Replacement Component, consistent with Good Utility Practice (such repair or replacement work, "Repairs"). The Manager shall provide notice (the "Repairs Notice") in writing to the Project Companies of (i) any required Repairs, (ii) the proposed scope of the Repairs (the "Proposed Repairs") including the material components to be used in such Proposed Repairs, which shall be Qualified Replacement Components, (iii) the estimated cost of the Repairs, and (iv) the anticipated commencement date and anticipated completion date of the work on such Repairs. No other notice of such Repairs shall be required except as such costs may be included in periodic financial and operating reports that may be required under this Agreement. Repairs with an aggregate cost greater than One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00) that are not required to ensure the continued safe operation of the Shared Facilities or to return the Shared Facilities to service, must be approved by all of the Project Companies. (b) If the Manager performs any Repairs, it shall (i) limit, to the extent commercially reasonable and subject to Good Utility Practice, any interference with the use by the Project Companies of the Shared Facilities and Easement Area during construction activities, (ii) except in the event of an Emergency, (A) schedule during an off-peak and/or low generation down-time period any required disconnection of the Shared Facilities to conduct construction activities in order to minimize any adverse impact on the Project Companies' Project, and (B) provide at least thirty (30) days prior written notice of commencement of such construction activities together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, and (iii) comply with the requirements of the SCE with respect thereto. (c) The Manager or another Project Company performing any Repairs (with respect to such Repairs) shall have the Project Companies and the Manager identified as beneficiaries of the warranties and indemnities obtained with respect to any Repairs. 5.5 Curtailment of Delivery. (a) The Manager may, in accordance with this Section 5.5, direct the Project Companies to interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power through the Shared Facilities (i) when necessary for the operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities; (ii) if the Manager determines, in its reasonable discretion, that interruption or reduction is necessary due to an Emergency; or (iii) at the direction of the Participating Transmission Owner pursuant to rights under the Interconnection Agreements. The Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to give the Project Companies as much advance notice as is reasonably possible of such interruptions, reductions or curtailments. 17 (b) With respect to any interruption or reduction of deliveries of electrical power pursuant to clauses (i) or (ii) of Section 5.5(a) the Manager shall curtail delivery of test power from any Project that is still in testing and has not reached commercial operation under its Interconnection Agreements before curtailing delivery of electric power from any Project that has reached commercial operation under its Interconnection Agreements and shall limit the length of any such interruption or curtailment to the minimum extent and minimum time strictly necessary to correct the problem; provided that any additional interruption or reduction of deliveries beyond curtailment of test power shall follow the curtailment priority in Section 5.5(c) below. Any interruption or curtailment made pursuant to clause (i) of Section 5.5(a) shall be made to the extent commercially reasonable during periods of low or no solar generation or low energy prices. (c) In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of the Participating Transmission Owner, such curtailment shall be allocated to the Projects in the following manner until such curtailment is achieved: (1) first, each Project Company (if any) that is delivering energy in excess of such Project Company's Maximum Capacity shall reduce deliveries down to such Project Company's Maximum Capacity, (2) second, each Project Company that is delivering test power shall reduce all such deliveries down to zero, (3) third, as provided in and to the extent applicable under Section 5.5(d)(2) each such Project Company shall reduce all such deliveries until all required curtailment has been applied fully or any or all such Projects to which such curtailments relate under Section 5.5(d)(2) have been fully curtailed; and (4) fourth, subject to Section 5.5(d)(1) to the extent its Project has not already been fully curtailed, each Project Company shall reduce its energy deliveries so that they do not exceed an amount (the "Curtailed Output Cap") equal to (X) such Project Company's Maximum Capacity, minus (Y) the product of (i) the aggregate number of MW then required for the Projects as a whole to curtail (after application of preceding clauses (c)(1), (2) and (3)) times (ii) such Project Company's Proportionate Share. provided that if during any relevant period of curtailment any Project Company is delivering energy at a level less than its Curtailed Output Cap (any such amount, a "Shortfall") either because such Project Company's Project is undergoing maintenance, has a forced outage, or other circumstance, then for so long as such Shortfall exists, each other Project Company may generate above such Project Company's Curtailed Output Cap by allocating the Shortfall to the other Project Company. (d) Notwithstanding the other provisions of this Section 5.5: (1) The Manager shall be authorized to curtail on a non-pro rata, but equitable and reasonable basis (as determined by the Manager in good faith) if (A) in spite of the Manager's good faith efforts to direct the Project Companies to comply with this Section 5.5 curtailment of deliveries from the Projects as directed by the Participating Transmission Owner is not otherwise achievable, (B) such non-pro rata allocation is otherwise necessary to comply with the Interconnection Agreements or the Participating Transmission Owner's direction, or (C) such non-pro rata allocation is necessary to give WDAT 1203 priority over the WDAT 1281 and, in each of the foregoing clauses (A), (B) and (C), that such non-pro rata allocation will not result in a default under the Interconnection Agreements; and (2) To the extent that the need for any curtailment, interruption or reduction can be attributed to a particular Project Company's Project or portions of its Project or the failure of such Project to comply with the order to curtail or a default by such Project Company under this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreements, or an applicable Power Purchase Agreement, or to the extent such Project Company's Project is the cause of an Emergency Condition, then all such curtailment shall be allocated to such Project Company and such Project Company will be responsible for all costs, liabilities and damages, including lost revenues, resulting from such curtailment (subject to the limitations in this Agreement) and the Manager shall, to the extent possible, limit such interruption or reduction to such Project or such portions of the Project, as the case may be. (e) Each Project Company shall promptly implement such curtailment, interruption in, or reduction of, delivery as the Manager shall direct pursuant to this Section 5.5. In the event notice is impracticable or if a Project Company fails to promptly comply therewith, the Manager may take direct action to implement such curtailment, interruption or reduction. A Project Company that fails to implement any such curtailment, interruption or reduction, shall be responsible for all cost and expenses related thereto, including deviation or imbalance charges and penalties assessed by the CAISO. In order to facilitate the scheduling of outages and disconnections of the Shared Facilities, each Project Company shall provide written notice to the Manager of any and all scheduled outage requirements set forth in its Power Purchase Agreement, if any, by the later of thirty (30) days after the Agreement Date or the date of execution of the Power Purchase Agreement. Thereafter on or before December 31 of each year, or such earlier date as required under a Power Purchase Agreement, each Project Company shall provide to the Manager its forecasted scheduled outages of its Project for the next calendar year. The Manager shall make all commercially reasonable efforts to schedule Repairs in a manner that is consistent with the Project Company's scheduled outage requirements and the outage scheduling requirements of the Interconnection Agreements. 19 5.6 Disconnection of Shared Facilities. The Manager shall have the power and authority to disconnect the Project of a Project Company from the Shared Facilities (a) pursuant to Sections 9.3 or 9.5 upon liquidation and removal of the Shared Facilities, (b) as provided in Article 10 upon certain defaults hereunder, (c) if necessary, consistent with Good Utility Practice for the operation and maintenance of any portion of the Shared Facilities, or (d) if the Manager determines, in its good faith discretion, that disconnection is necessary in the event of an Emergency or to otherwise prevent damage or injury to persons or property, including to the other Projects, the Shared Facilities, the Interconnection Facilities or the property of the Participating Transmission Owner or as otherwise needed to prevent or mitigate technical issues affecting the Shared Facilities, provided that the Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to give the Project Companies as much advance notice as is reasonably possible under the circumstances, consistent with responding to the Emergency or preventing damage or injury to persons or property, or (e) at the direction of the Participating Transmission Owner pursuant to rights under the Interconnection Agreements. Unless the Manager has in its good faith determined that it is unable to do so because an imminent threat of injury or death to persons, or damage to property exists, the Manager shall provide notice to the relevant Project Companies prior to or concurrently with disconnecting its Project from the Shared Facilities or as soon thereafter as is reasonably practical. In the event the Manager determines that any such disconnection is necessary, the Project Companies shall provide to the Manager promptly upon request such Project operational and control data as the Manager may consider necessary to implement such disconnection. 5.7 Books and Records; Reporting Requirements. (a) Maintenance of Records. The Manager shall maintain books and records related to the Easement Property Rights and the Shared Facilities in sufficient detail to verify amounts incurred by the Manager and/or due and payable hereunder for a period of not less than five (5) years after the end of the calendar month to which they relate or such longer period as may be required by applicable law, and all such books and records shall be available for inspection and/or copying by each Party or its authorized representative at the cost and expense of such Party and at reasonable times during regular business hours, upon reasonable notice to the Manager. The costs incurred by the Manager in performing its obligations pursuant to this Section 5.7(a) shall be Shared O M Expenses and shall be automatically added to the then current Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget if not already included. (b) Provision of Records. The Manager shall, from time to time and no later than thirty (30) days after the end of each calendar quarter, provide written reports to the Project Companies sufficient to keep the Project Companies reasonably apprised as to significant matters concerning the maintenance and repair of the Easement Area and Shared Facilities, including such matters related thereto as may have a material impact on the operation, maintenance and repair of each Project Company's Project. The costs incurred by the Manager in performing its obligations pursuant to this Section 5.7(b) shall be Shared O M Expenses and shall be automatically added to the then current Approved Shared Facilities O M Budget if not already included. 20 (c) Audits. Each Project Company shall have the right to audit and make copies of the Manager's books and records for the Shared Facilities and the Easement Property Rights, including with respect to construction costs for approved Additional Facilities and Shared O M Expenses, during normal business hours and upon reasonable advance notice to the Manager; provided that the Project Company requesting such audit shall be responsible for all costs associated with such audit, including reimbursing the Manager for any costs incurred by the Manager in responding to such request and in the performance of such audit. Seller will make wholesale electric energy, capacity, and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below. 2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all sales of energy, capacity, and ancillary services by Seller not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule of Seller. 3. Rates. All sales shall be made at the rates established between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 5. Compliance with Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller’s market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff. 6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market Based Rate Authority. Seller does not have any limitations on its market-based rate authority except as otherwise provided in this Tariff. The Commission granted Seller in RB Inyokern Solar WDAT 1203 LLC, Docket No. ER24-1346-000 (April 24, 2024) (unpublished letter order) the following waivers and blanket authorization: (a) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission’s regulations requiring the filing of cost-of-service information, except for Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; (b) waiver of the requirements of Part 41 and Part 101, with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects; (c) waiver of Part 141 of the Commission’s regulations concerning accounting and reporting requirements, with the exception of 18 C.F.R. § 141.15; and (d) blanket approval as to Section 204 of the FPA and Part 34 of the Commission’s regulations for all future issuances of securities and debt and assumption of liabilities. 7. Ancillary Services. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (“PJM”) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (“CAISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (“SPP”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization.
